Q) I have XXXX for trade, are you interested?
A) NO, thank you, but not interested in any trades.

Q) Can we just do a bill of sale, I have a lifetime carry permit?
A) NO, through the FFL, sorry

A) Well first, that isn't a question, that is a statement. Second, NO you will not give me $450 because my price is $500. I am firm at that price, if it doesn't sell, oh well.

A) Again, that isn't a question, that is a statement. If you can get it here or there for this or that, GREAT, go get it. I know what the prices are locally and online and mine is well within reason, even for a used Beretta.

Q) Do you have any extras?

Inland M1A1 Paratrooper .30 caliber Carbine from 1943. 
Inland Div. and serial number is under the rear sight, partially visible.
US Carbine Cal. 30 M1 is on top at the base of the barrel.
Inland MFG. General Motors, 1-43 is on the top at the front of the barrel
N is marked on the front sight.
Inland is stamped on the Trigger housing assembly.
co M is marked on the Magazine catch.
P.I is stamped inside the operating slide.
KI is marked on the Front band assembly.
TH is stamped on the hammer.
M or W is stamped on the hook of the bolt. 
Rear sight is marked I.R.CO 7160060 
There are no markings on the stock and it seems to be a later replacement.
Original Bayonet marked U.S.M4 UTICA with the flame stamp.
Bayonet holster has USM8 BMCO marked at the top. 
It looks very nice and clean. Bore is shiny. Stock is excellent, and metal is very good with aprox 95% dark. Everything works as it should. This is a very hard to find original with all the major parts of the metal assembly made and marked by Inland. It comes with one 15 rounds magazine.

A new m1a1 paratrooper reproduction sells for $1500

REDACTED

This is a piece of history, in excellent shape and working condition, priced to sell quick.
You can see more pictures at backpage.com in Phoenix area.

title: For Sale:  BARRETT REC7
postcontent:
Barrett REC 7 5.56mm Rifle with Two 30 round PMAGS and the Tactical Soft Carry Case. The REC7 rifle’s dependability stems largely from its innovative operating system. Using a minimum number of parts, the piston system separates heat and powder residue from the bolt carrier and trigger assembly. The rifle runs cool and clean, reducing maintenance requirements and increasing endurance. The patented chrome-lined fluted gas block prevents excessive carbon buildup from operation under adverse conditions. The one-piece 17-4 stainless piston transfers energy to the anti-tilt bolt carrier. Machined from a monolithic block of 8620 steel, the carrier features an integral piston strike face.

The Barrett Enhanced Bolt is made from high-strength 9310 steel. The bolt is designed specifically for use in the piston operated REC7, not just adapted from a direct gas bolt. The bolt’s gas-ring-free design is easy to clean. Reinforced at critical areas, every bolt is proofed and magnetic-particle inspected to guarantee reliable performance. See the pictures.

At the heart of the operating system is a nitrided, two-position, forward-venting gas plug that retains the piston. The piston can be accessed through the front of the gas block without removing the hand guard so optical sights or laser devices do not need to be zeroed after routine maintenance.

The REC7 rifle’s forged 7075 aluminum upper and lower receivers are Type 3 hard coat anodized. The lower houses an ultra-dependable single-stage trigger. The upper supports a free-floated, hammer-forged, chrome-lined 16” 1in7 twist barrel with M4 feed ramps machined into the receiver and the barrel extension. A mil-spec A2 flash hider protects the muzzle.
